content: I will go through with you the most interesting games
from Helsinki Open tournament played over week ago
Tournament was played with a new rule
Peter Jonsson's rule, he is the chairman of RIF
1. Black player opens according to RIF rules
2. 2nd player can swap already if wants to
3. White player then places 4th move freely
same time announces whether black must make 1, 2 or 3 alternative 5th moves
4. Black player can swap after this
5. White player then removes all but one 5th choice and game continues normally.
it sounds more tricky than is
basically, it supports all theories, but gives a chance to play more interesting variants if players wish to
You will get a feeling about the rule, when I introduce the games
we were joined by Karlssons and Jonssons from Sweden
and a strong line-up of Estonian starts, only missing Ando
it was expected, that Stefan Karlsson along with the Estonians would fight for the top places
Now, with the check-up lets see some games !

yuelee00, skywalker, Yue, endlessroad, mayhem, sirasoni, xiaoxiaohua, slappanu, xinxin, bergamot, benben, alicecooper, Samsone, Adun, callings, flora, derkas, yysanyue, dreamy, lkogr, Ikon, Shangjin, xiaoxin, Torsten, mima, jiaren.
1st round offered few very interesting starting pairs
first game shows Aivo Oll vs. Timo Ilu, Estonian young talents
made possible by the new rule
Aivo made 4th move, and said black must make 3 alternative moves here
which ones would you choose to offer ?
I mean, which 5th moves you would offer
I am not familiar with this opening. i8,i7,j6
I mean Aivo's choices, Timo forced Aivo to make the moves
can you guess which one Timo left on board
black responded in a seemingly logical way
and gives powerful play to white
but before that, could black play differently
nice play from Timo all over
perhaps this 5th move was already mistake
Stefan KArlsson faced Andry Purk from Estonia too
white offered only one 5th alternative with this 4th move
are you familiar with this position ?
me neither really, this 5th seldom played
one could get to this position from i5
but in i5 mostly 5 is played at j8
here the position seems quite free for trying
14 is a try to cut the whole left side space away
Andry played a very active, brave attempt
it is double win, can you see ?
I was around their table when they played
and Andry was explaining somethin about he making the 18th cause he didn't quite see the next move
so in conclusion, the 18 is too brave
and it has, as you see, a good basis to win

3rd interesting game on 1st round, atleast on Finnish viewpoint, was between Marko Pellikka and Peter Jonsson
Peter often plays variants that are advantageous for black
you are free to speak your mind :))
knowledge says it's a common variant in d3
I do not know myself either
but it seems to be poorer than i11
but Peter is risky player, most likely Marko did not know this move so well either
15 is often used attack move in d3 variants
Marko tried to keep tempo carefully
black pretty well in charge all around
so, I will let Marko know :)
great, but if 32 - h10, harder to find a straight win
37 is great, maybe a win already
you can test defenses here if you want
probably Marko made the right choice
black needs E7 support in order to win below
Marko was a bit worried about this chance when he played 37
so Marko played well, not easy always to win as black in D3
was played a very decisive game
between Timo Ilu and Johann Lents
and surprised me with his tactics
let's see your tactics on the lesson :)

Johann chose this famous draw variant
where is the draw move here ?
maybe preparation, probably an inspiration during the arly game
dreamy, do you know this variant ?
black managed to gain some activity on top side
and did not force attack on crowded space
maybe 44 was not good enough, but black got a powerful attack
only problem is now to connect upper to lwer
Timo started to realize black has winning opportunity
but too late, Johann had it figured
Timo tried to trick with clever bocks
but all was clear to black
this win was based mostly by the surprising 31st move
hard to say, where white could have saved
44 raises a question to me, maybe worthy of a homework to you
two fighters met also on 2nd round
how many of you have played this ?
ok so we are in strange waters
seemingly black attack here is difficult
black can make a free move next,
white can not start a powerful attack somewhere else
clearly aiming for F5 stretching to control the whole lower side
Stefan as usual plays very strong ideas in defense
here black can not make a careless attack to left
white might build strongly on right
Seemingly, white shouild not blindly follow this move
it would probably allow black to attack afterwards
so Stefan cuts connection to 15th, creating support for stones 16, 18
a skillful defense serving many purposes
with the following moves, white has now ruined black's space around 19th
after 25 it's time to think again
black might easily surround whites all around and force atleast draw
or maybe black can even make attack
also on row 3 black can make trouble
so white makes helpful defense moves
but is nonetheless forced to make passive defense
but this way white ensured black can not win on lower side, or left side
Ants was forced after 34 into a long battle
so, maybe I have time to show someting from 3rd round too today
first let's wake the sleepers for few seconds :)

on 3rd round, Tunnet Taimla faced Johann
as Johann beat Timo, he and Tunnet were my favorites for tour win
and what can you say about your experiences ?
and now is forced to defend
Tunnet's play with black's is good, it has so much purpose
32 is quite necessary, k9 very strong point
white can not create practically anything with his stones after 27
after 29th it seemed only like black just cruises to victory
black needed a stone like 29, to make 31 so dangerous
otherwise white could have blocked more tightly, and the lower side maybe not enough for win
but since 32 is not intact, then 33 seems to be enough to win
I apologize for not having a mre organized session for this evening
But these games played by these Estonian young masters are so good, that we should enjoy them together
I will continue showing tournament games next week
You do a good job GM
and maybe even week after that, many more interesting games left to see
I thank you all for this evening
thanks GM for the nice lesson!
and hope to see you next week also
